    <h2>‚ùì What</h2>
    <p>Users, internal and external, are not just the source of issues. They are also the source of important information about how the products and services you provide are used in the wild. Don't be afraid to ask them, what is bothering them. If you have multiple possible solutions for an issue - check with the users, who reported it, they may have a better idea what will work for their flows. Try to gather information about different aspects of the product in one place as source of truth and keep relevant people up-to-date on important changes.</p>
    <h2>ü™ô Business impact</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Lack of knowledge</li>
        <li>Echo chamber of ideas</li>
        <li>Feeling of non-importance</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>‚ùå Poor implementation</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Minimizes or completely removes self-help opportunities.</li>
        <li>Promotes siloed organization structure with no information exchange.</li>
        <li>Blindsides to improvement opportunities and early issue recognition.</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>‚úÖ Good implementation</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Frees agent's time to focus on more complex issues.</li>
        <li>Creates knowledgebase which can be relied on by everyone for complex investigations and onboarding.</li>
        <li>Increases morale by timely recognition of ideas and achievements.</li>
    </ul>
