    <h2>üí° Tips</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Have an easy way to gather "user voices" to know about what's good, what's bad and what's needed.</li>
        <li>If using public forums ensure they have a good logical structure and moderate them properly, but try not to censor too much.</li>
        <li>When collecting ideas, consider making the process public, so that other users can vote on them, and also keep the status of those ideas up-to-date.</li>
        <li>Avoid multiple sources of information about the product, where possible, to have single source of truth.</li>
        <li>If using multiple sources of information, ensure cross-linking for easier discoverability.</li>
        <li>Have an easy and convenient way to search for information for both internal and external users.</li>
        <li>Encourage people involved in support to create or update knowledgebase articles based on resolved tickets.</li>
        <li>Have appropriate review process for changes in the knowledgeable, but allow skipping of it in case of minor changes, while still tracking history of the changes.</li>
        <li>Consider periodic live demos of the product's new features or significant changes.</li>
        <li>Consider "Sit in my chair" initiatives for employees to try work in a different role for some time (especially for devs and product leads trying out support with live people).</li>
        <li>When possible involve developers and product team (at least) in direct support to better see what issues are happening at specific moments.</li>
        <li>Encourage direct communication with clients for all levels of support, when such communication makes sense.</li>
        <li>Consider having at least 1 developer (on rotation) from each team who will prioritize assistance with support tickets.</li>
        <li>If an implemented idea was shared or a critical issue was identified by an external user be sure to thank them: a smile is also a sort of KPI.</li>
        <li>Add a support representative to change management and project reviews, since they may see gaps, that other can't.</li>
        <li>When possible do end-2-end tests with actual users of the product (UAT or beta programs).</li>
    </ul>
